  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Emerged from efforts to combat organized crime in the early 20th century\n- Initially focused on tracking criminal proceeds and financial transactions\n\n2. United States Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major anti-money laundering legislation\n- Required financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Developments\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a global issue\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Developed international standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Specifically criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- Expanded legal framework for prosecuting financial crimes\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Strengthened anti-money laundering regulations\n- Enhanced international cooperation\n- Expanded requirements for financial institutions\n\n6. Recent Trends\n- Increased focus on cryptocurrency and digital transaction monitoring\n- More sophisticated international legal frameworks\n- Expanded regulatory compliance requirements\n\nThis overview highlights the evolution of money laundering legal prohibitions over time.",
